  Authentication

.max-w-prose
  = doc_info(url: "https://github.com/omniauth/omniauth", icon: "lock-closed", icon_css: "text-primary") do
    :markdown
      _Loco_**Motion** recommends starting with **OmniAuth** for authentication
      — its `:developer` strategy gets you signing in fast.

.prose
  :markdown
    # Authentication &amp; Error Handling

    This guide covers adding user authentication with **OmniAuth**, plus the
    in-browser error tools (**Web Console** and **BetterErrors**) that make
    debugging the sign-in flow painless. It assumes you have already followed
    the [Getting Started guide](#{guide_path("getting_started")}) and have a
    running Dockerized Rails app.

.mt-12.prose
  :markdown
    ## 1. Authentication with OmniAuth

    There are a **lot** of ways to handle authentication in Rails. The two
    most popular gems are
    [OmniAuth](https://github.com/omniauth/omniauth) and
    [Devise](https://github.com/heartcombo/devise).

    We recommend starting with OmniAuth because its `:developer` strategy lets
    you get going very quickly, and you can
    [integrate it with Devise](https://github.com/heartcombo/devise#omniauth)
    or a service like [Auth0](https://auth0.com/) later if you choose.

    Add the relevant gems to your `Gemfile` and re-run `bundle install`:

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "ruby") do
    :plain
      # Gemfile
      gem "omniauth"
      gem "omniauth-rails_csrf_protection"

= doc_note(modifier: :tip, title: "Restarting Quickly", css: "mt-6") do
  :markdown
    After installing, you will need to restart your Rails server. Rather than
    a full restart, you can restart just the web process by touching a file:
    <br /><br />
    ```
    touch tmp/restart.txt
    ```

.mt-6.prose
  :markdown
    Next, create an OmniAuth initializer:

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "ruby") do
    :plain
      # config/initializers/omniauth.rb
      Rails.application.config.middleware.use OmniAuth::Builder do
        provider :developer if Rails.env.development?
      end

.mt-6.prose
  :markdown
    Add the routes for the login page and the provider callback:

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "ruby") do
    :plain
      # config/routes.rb
      get "/auth/:provider/callback", to: "sessions#create"
      get "/login", to: "sessions#new"

.mt-6.prose
  :markdown
    Then add a sessions controller and a simple login view:

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "ruby") do
    :plain
      # app/controllers/sessions_controller.rb
      class SessionsController < ApplicationController
        def new
          render :new
        end

        def create
          user_info = request.env["omniauth.auth"]
          raise user_info # Your own session management should be placed here.

          session[:user_info] = user_info.to_hash

          redirect_to root_path
        end
      end

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "haml") do
    :plain
      -# app/views/sessions/new.html.haml
      - if Rails.env.development?
        = form_tag("/auth/developer", method: "post", data: { turbo: false }) do
          %button.btn{ type: "submit" }
            Login with Developer

.mt-6.prose
  :markdown
    Visit [http://localhost:3000/login](http://localhost:3000/login), click
    the button, and enter any name and email. Because of the `raise user_info`
    line, the app will throw an error and show you exactly where it stopped —
    which is the perfect excuse to wire up better error tooling before we
    finish the flow.

    When you are ready for sign-in to actually work, delete or comment out the
    `raise user_info` line and integrate `session[:user_info]` into your app.

.mt-12.prose
  :markdown
    ## 2. Web Console

    Rails ships with [Web Console](https://github.com/rails/web-console), which
    inserts an IRB prompt right into your browser whenever an exception is
    raised. When running inside Docker, you will usually see a log line like:

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "text") do
    :plain
      Cannot render console from 172.23.0.1! Allowed networks: 127.0.0.0/127.255.255.255, ::1

.mt-6.prose
  :markdown
    Because we are on a different network than Rails expects, the console is
    blocked. Add the following to `config/environments/development.rb` to
    allow it no matter which IP the container uses:

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "ruby") do
    :plain
      # Fix console permissions for Docker so Web Console works no matter the IP
      config.web_console.permissions = "0.0.0.0/0"

.mt-6.prose
  :markdown
    Restart the app (using `just app-restart`) and refresh the login flow.
    You should now see a black, interactive console at the bottom of the error
    page. Type the following and hit enter to inspect the user you just signed
    in as:

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "ruby") do
    :plain
      user_info.to_hash

.mt-6.prose
  :markdown
    You can run almost any code here that you could run in your controllers,
    views, or models. A handy trick: drop a non-existent reference like `asdf`
    just above the code you want to inspect and refresh — Rails will stop
    there and let you poke around the live application state.

.mt-12.prose
  :markdown
    ## 3. BetterErrors (Optional)

    [BetterErrors](https://github.com/BetterErrors/better_errors) provides (in
    our humble opinion) a nicer interface for the errors that crop up in a
    Rails app. We particularly like how it lays the stack trace out to the
    left of the code and console.

    Add the following to the `:development` group of your `Gemfile`:

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "ruby") do
    :plain
      # Gemfile
      group :development do
        gem "better_errors"
        gem "binding_of_caller"
      end

= doc_note(modifier: :error, title: "Security Note", css: "mt-6") do
  :markdown
    It is **imperative** that these live in the `:development` group so they
    can never load in production — otherwise you create a **massive** security
    risk!

.mt-6.prose
  :markdown
    Run `bundle install` inside the app container (`just app-shell`), or
    simply kill and restart it with `just app-fast`, which installs new gems
    for you. Because we are inside Docker, BetterErrors will also refuse
    connections from the host machine. Add the following to
    `config/environments/development.rb`:

.mt-6.max-w-prose
  = doc_code(language: "ruby") do
    :plain
      # Allow BetterErrors to render
      BetterErrors::Middleware.allow_ip! "0.0.0.0/0"

.mt-6.prose
  :markdown
    Restart your container (e.g. `just app-restart`) and refresh the page to
    get the fully-featured error screen — perfect for inspecting that
    `raise user_info` line before you finish wiring up sign-in.

